🍄 A Mario Theme Guestbook & Profile
A fun, Mario‑themed web application that combines a guestbook and a personal profile page. Users can sign the guestbook and view/edit a detailed Mario‑inspired profile with custom avatar, stats, skills, and photo albums. Built with React, Vite, and Supabase.

✨ Features
Guestbook (World 1-1)
Sign the guestbook: Enter your name, choose a character (Mario, Luigi, Peach, etc.), your country, and a message.

Adventurer Log: View all guestbook entries in reverse chronological order.

Coin counter: Collect coins by hitting the ? blocks in the header – coins persist via localStorage.

Responsive design: Works on all screen sizes with a classic Mario aesthetic.

Profile (World 1-2)
Custom avatar: Upload a profile picture URL (supports direct image links).

Profile stats: Coins collected, worlds completed, extra lives, power level.

About Me and detailed profile info (location, occupation, specialty, website).

Skills section: Display your technical skills with Mario‑style badges.

Photo albums: Four separate carousels for Friends, Inspirations, Academic, and My Hobby.

Each album has its own left/right navigation.

Click any photo to open a full‑screen lightbox with keyboard navigation.

Edit profile: Inline form to update all profile fields.

Shared
HUD (Heads‑Up Display): Always‑visible top bar showing current world and coin count.

Animated backgrounds: Scrolling clouds, floating stars, and ground pipes.

Supabase backend: All guestbook entries and profile data are stored in Supabase.

🛠 Technologies Used
Frontend: React 19, Vite, React Router DOM

Styling: Pure CSS with Mario‑themed custom properties (no UI libraries)

Backend: Supabase (PostgreSQL database, Row Level Security, REST API)

Deployment: Vercel

Version Control: Git / GitHub

🚀 Getting Started
Prerequisites
Node.js (v18 or later)

npm or yarn

A Supabase account (free tier)

1. Clone the Repository
bash
git clone https://github.com/efl-ward/mobprog_finals.git
cd mario-guestbook
2. Install Dependencies
bash
npm install
3. Set Up Supabase
Create a new Supabase project.

Run the SQL script in supabase/schema.sql to create the required tables and RLS policies:

guestbook – stores guestbook entries

mario_profile – stores profile data (including avatar_url)

hobbies – stores hobby cards 

Copy your project URL and anon key from Supabase → Project Settings → API.

4. Configure Environment Variables
Create a .env file in the project root with:

text
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=your_supabase_project_url
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your_supabase_anon_key
5. Run the Development Server
bash
npm run dev
Visit http://localhost:5173 (or the Codespaces URL) to see the app.

